body:
Consider this code (it is minimal reproducible example):

```rust
fn f(_: &[u8]) {
}

fn main() {
    let b = Box::new([0u8; 1000]);
    f(&b);
}
```

It doesn't compile, and I don't like this.
https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=1a1a8a172c0e3c580c2faa261694ee6a

Now let me describe why I need this to compile. I. e. let me tell you my actual problem. I have a wrapper for `libc::read` called `read_repeatedly` with this signature: `pub fn read_repeatedly(fildes: c_int, buf: &mut [u8]) -> Result<&mut [u8], Errno>`. I tried to allocate a buffer so: `let mut buf = box [0u8; 10_000]`. I allocated it in heap, because I'm afraid of getting stack overflow. And I used `box` instead of `Box::new`, because I'm afraid that `Box::new([0u8; 10_000])` first allocates a buffer on stack and then moves it to box (I have read about this problem here: https://github.com/PoignardAzur/placement-by-return/blob/placement-by-return/text/0000-placement-by-return.md ). I used a box instead of vec, because I think one should always use box unless he really needs a vec.

Then I did this: `read_repeatedly(socket2, &mut buf)`. And it did not work. I was able to fix the code so: `read_repeatedly(socket2, buf.as_mut())`. Still I think original code should work.

Yes, this bug is probably not a bug. I. e. the compiler probably works as intended. But still current behavior is confusing. I see clear path how the value should be coerced: `&mut Box<[u8; 10_000]>` -> `&mut [u8; 10_000]` -> `&mut [u8]`
